The bug in the function `isEven(n)` is that it returns `1` or `0`, which are truthy and falsy values in JavaScript, but not explicit `true` or `false` boolean values. To fix this, you should compare the result of `n % 2` to `0` to explicitly return a boolean value.

Here is the fixed code:

```javascript
function isEven(n) {
    return n % 2 === 0;
}
```

In this fixed version, `n % 2 === 0` will return `true` if `n` is even and `false` if `n` is odd.
